definition.value: A dihydroxybenzenesulfonic acid that is resorcinol in which the hydrogen ortho- to both of the hydroxy groups is replaced by a sulfonic acid group.
A dihydroxybenzenesulfonic acid that is resorcinol in which the hydrogen meta- to both of the hydroxy groups is replaced by a sulfonic acid group.
A pyrroledicarboxylic acid in which the two carboxy groups are located at positions 2 and 5.
A pyrroledicarboxylic acid in which the two carboxy groups are located at positions 3 and 4.
A 2-enoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the enoic carboxy group of hex-2-enedioic acid.
A lactoyl-CoA in which the lactoyl residue has (R)-configuration.
A ceramide phosphate that is N-acyl-15-methylhexadecasphing-4-enine bearing a single phospho substituent at position 1.
An N-acyl-L-alanine resulting from the formal condensation of L-alanine with the carboxy group of benzoic acid.
An N-acylamino acid that is the N-benzoyl derivative of alanine.

A compound that blocks the processing of the Gag precursor protein in HIV-1 by the viral protease enzyme, leading to the formation of noninfectious, immature virus particles that are incapable of infecting other cells.
An aspartic acid derivative that is L-aspartic acid in which one of the amine hydrogens is substituted by a 9-beta-D-ribofuranosyl-9H-purin-6-yl group.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is olean-12-ene substituted by hydroxy groups at 3beta and 27-positions and a carboxy group at position 28.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specifed as cyclohex-1-en-1-ylcarbonyl.
A histamine agonist that binds to and activates H1-receptors.
A dihydropterin that is monapterin dihydrogenated at positions 7 and 8.
A butan-4-olide that is dihydrofuran-2-one substituted at C-3 and C-4 by hydroxy groups (the 3R,4S-diastereomer).
A tetrahydropterin that is monapterin tetrahydrogenated at positions 5, 6, 7 and 8.
An EC 2.1.1.* (methyltransferases) inhibitor that interferes with the action of N-acetylserotonin methyltransferase (EC 2.1.1.4).
An O-acylcarnitine compound having trans-2-methyl-2-butenoyl (tiglyl) as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine compound having 2-ethylacryloyl as the acyl substituent.
An EC 3.5.1.98 (histone deacetylase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of Sir2.
An N-alkylpyrrolidine that is cotinine substituted at position C-3 by a hydroxy group (the 3R,5S-diastereomer).
An organic anion that is the monoanion obtained by the deprotonation of the 2-hydroxy group of 2-hydroxy-3-(2-hydroxyethyl)naphthalene-1,4-dione.
A naphthoquinone that is naphthalene-1,4-dione substituted by a hydroxy group and a 2-hydroxyethyl group at positions 2 and 3 respectively.
A methyl ester that is methyl phenylacetate substituted at the alpha-position by a cyanomethyl group.
A steroid acid that has a carboxy group located at the 4alpha-position and a hydroxy substituent located at the 3beta-position.
An alicyclic ketone that is cyclopentanone substituted at position 3 by a cyano group.
A secondary amino compound that is ammonia in which two of the hydrogens are substituted by cyanomethyl groups.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 4-methoxy-4-oxo-3-phenylbutanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-oxocyclopentanecarboxylic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-(cyanomethyl)glycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A lipopeptide that is an analogue of human GLP-1 in which the lysine residue at position 27 is replaced by arginine and a hexadecanoyl group attached to the remaining lysine via a glutamic acid spacer. Used as an adjunct to diet and exercise to improve glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes mellitus.
An agonist that binds to and activates glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptors.
A citrate salt obtained by combining equimolar amounts of tofacitinib and citric acid. Used to treat moderately to severely active Rheumatoid Arthritis.
A 2-hydroxy-6-oxohexa-2,4-dienoate in which the double bonds at positions 2 and 4 have Z- and E-configuration respectively.
An organophosphonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of hydroxymethylphosphonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of one of the phosphonate OH groups.

A pyrrolopyrimidine that is pyrrolo[2,3-d]pyrimidine substituted at position 4 by an N-methyl,N-(1-cyanoacetyl-4-methylpiperidin-3-yl)amino moiety. Used as its citrate salt to treat moderately to severely active rheumatoid arthritis.
A quinolinemonocarboxylate that is the conjugate base of xanthurenic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of bepotastine.
beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-D-GlcpNAc in which the configuration of the anomeric centre of the reducing-end N-acetylglucosamine residue is beta.

An ether that is (S)-(4-chlorophenyl)(pyridin-2-yl)methanol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen is substituted by a 1-(3-carboxypropyl)piperidin-4-yl group. A topical, selective and non-sedating histamine (H1) receptor antagonist used (as its benzenesulfonate salt) for treatment of itching associated with allergic conjunctivitis.

beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-D-GlcpNAc in which the configuration of the anomeric centre of the reducing-end N-acetylglucosamine residue is beta.

An amino trisaccharide comprised of a linear sequence of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine linked (1->4) and (1->6); beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->6)-D-GalpNAc with alpha anomeric configuration at the reducing-end.
A 2-hydroxy-6-oxohexa-2,4-dienoic acid in which the double bonds at positions 2 and 4 have Z- and E-configuration respectively.
An amino tetrasaccharide comprised of a linear sequence of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, beta-D-galactose and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked (1->4), (1->6) and (1->4).
A nitrile that is the N-cyanomethyl derivative of glycine.
A disaccharide consisting of beta-D-glucuronic acid linked (1->3) to a beta-D-galactose residue.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of (4-coumaroyl)acetyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
Any intra-glandular substance that acts as a precursor of a hormone, usually having minimal hormonal effect itself. Prohormones generally help in amplifying the effect of existing hormones.
